A stack overflow occurs when recursion goes too deep — each function call adds a stack frame, and the call stack has a fixed size limit (typically ~1-8 MB, ~10k-100k frames).

Common causes in 281:
- DFS on a large graph with O(V) depth (path graph of 100k nodes)
- Unoptimized recursion (e.g., naive Fibonacci with n=50 makes 2^50 calls — but this is also exponential time)
- Missing or incorrect base case → infinite recursion

Fixes:
1. **Convert to iterative with explicit stack**:
```cpp
// Recursive DFS → iterative DFS
stack<int> stk;
stk.push(start);
while (!stk.empty()) {
    int u = stk.top(); stk.pop();
    if (visited[u]) continue;
    visited[u] = true;
    for (int v : adj[u]) if (!visited[v]) stk.push(v);
}
```
2. **Increase stack size** (Linux): `ulimit -s unlimited` — not portable, not preferred
3. **Tail recursion**: restructure so the recursive call is the last operation; some compilers optimize this
4. **Memoization → tabulation**: convert recursive DP to iterative bottom-up

For competitive programming and EECS 281 projects with large inputs, always convert deep recursion to iterative when input size could exceed ~10k.

A lambda is an anonymous function object defined inline. Syntax:
```cpp
[capture](parameters) -> return_type { body }
```
The return type is usually inferred and can be omitted.

Capture list — how the lambda accesses outer variables:
- `[]`: capture nothing
- `[=]`: capture all by value (copy)
- `[&]`: capture all by reference
- `[x, &y]`: capture x by value, y by reference

Common uses in EECS 281:
```cpp
// Custom sort comparator
sort(v.begin(), v.end(), [](int a, int b) { return a > b; });

// Custom priority queue comparator
auto cmp = [](pair<int,int> a, pair<int,int> b) { return a.first > b.first; };
priority_queue<pair<int,int>, vector<pair<int,int>>, decltype(cmp)> pq(cmp);

// With capture
int threshold = 5;
auto isLarge = [threshold](int x) { return x > threshold; };
auto it = find_if(v.begin(), v.end(), isLarge);

// Recursive lambda (needs std::function)
function<int(int)> fact = [&](int n) { return n <= 1 ? 1 : n * fact(n-1); };
```

Note: lambdas captured by reference can dangle if they outlive the scope. Capture by value when the lambda might outlive the current scope.

STL provides std::next_permutation for enumerating permutations. For subsets, use bitmask or recursive backtracking.

**Permutations with next_permutation**:
```cpp
vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3};
sort(v.begin(), v.end());  // MUST start sorted for all permutations
do {
    // process v
} while (next_permutation(v.begin(), v.end()));
// Generates all n! permutations in lexicographic order
```

**Subsets with bitmask** (for small n ≤ 20):
```cpp
int n = v.size();
for (int mask = 0; mask < (1 << n); mask++) {
    vector<int> subset;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        if (mask & (1 << i)) subset.push_back(v[i]);
    // process subset
}
// Generates all 2^n subsets
```

**Recursive backtracking (more flexible)**:
```cpp
void genSubsets(vector<int>& v, int idx, vector<int>& current, vector<vector<int>>& results) {
    results.push_back(current);
    for (int i = idx; i < v.size(); i++) {
        current.push_back(v[i]);
        genSubsets(v, i+1, current, results);
        current.pop_back();  // backtrack
    }
}
```

Complexity: permutations O(n!·n), subsets O(2^n·n). These are only feasible for small n (≤ 12-15).
